welcome to the third edition of the stanford seiu bargaining update in connection with stanford university's cont page 1 issue 3 july 24 2009 from the stanford bargaining team welcome to the third edition of the stanford seiu bargaining update in connection with stanford university's contract negotiations with the service employees international union local 2007 seiu on july 7 2009 stanford and seiu began negotiations for a new collective bargaining agreement for approximately 1200 employees in schools and departments across the university including the slac national laboratory this weekly update which will be available during these negotiations will provide information about ideas and interests discussed options tentatively agreed to or other outcomes please disseminate the update as needed stanford and the seiu negotiations continue the stanford and seiu negotiating teams met on july 21 and 23 2009 to continue discussions regarding how best to address the parties expressed interests the discussions included a more in depth review of options potential solutions to issues surfaced generated by the management team the management team's primary focus and interests in these negotiations is to find ways to control costs enhance productivity and assure a quality workplace several specific areas of focus include units such as grounds and paint in land buildings and real estate where expenses are not competitive with the market some of the proposed options generated are particularly sensitive in nature given the potential impact on bargaining unit workers these options include outsourcing the grounds and paint units pay cuts furloughs new and more competitive job classifications reductions in staffing and improvements in workplace safety among others the discussions also surfaced options that would have lesser impact on bargaining unit workers these options include minimum staffing levels establishing new training apprenticeship classifications and reassigning impacted staff to other bargaining unit positions both the university and the seiu bargaining teams recognize that some of these are difficult topics but that they must be discussed in light of the current financial environment departments across the university have been forced to significantly reduce budgets based on reductions in funding and a decline in endowment performance the parties resume negotiations on tuesday july 28 2009 the stanford bargaining team the stanford bargaining team includes david a jones director employee & management services human resources ann allison marsh senior manager employee & labor relations human resources cori bossenberry director of human resources school of medicine robert carpenter director of operations buildings and grounds maintenance land buildings and real estate megan davis associate vice president page 2 issue 3 july 24 2009 finance land buildings and real estate eric montell executive director stanford dining residential and dining enterprises and larry young director of human resources slac national laboratory
